  "prompt": "What is the old name of Chennai?",
  "response": "Chennai, the capital city of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu, was formerly known as **Madras**. The name \"Madras\" was used during British colonial rule and continued after India gained independence in 1947. It wasn't until 1996 that the city was officially renamed \"Chennai\" to better reflect its Tamil heritage and cultural identity.\n\n### Historical Context:\n\n- **Madras Era (1640\u20131996):**\n  - The city was founded in 1639 as a trading post by the British East India Company and was officially named Madras in 1640.\n  - The origin of the name \"Madras\" is believed to be derived from \"Madraspatnam,\" a corruption of the Portuguese phrase \"Madraspattinam.\" Another theory suggests it was named after a local landowner, Damarla Chennappa Nayakudu.\n\n- **Renaming to Chennai (1996):**\n  - In an effort to shed its colonial legacy and embrace its indigenous roots, the government of Tamil Nadu officially changed the city's name to Chennai.\n  - \"Chennai\" is believed to be derived from \"Chennapattanam,\" named after Chennappa Nayakudu, a local ruler or influential figure in the region's history.\n\nThe renaming of Madras to Chennai was part of a broader movement in India to replace colonial-era names with names that reflect local languages, culture, and history.",
